		"text": "you use an old compiler binary that didn&#x27;t have the attack yet to compile the latest source code that it is able to compile, then use that compile the latest it can compile, and so forth.<p>what I mean is that I wouldn&#x27;t expect a the 2012 rust prerelease to be able to compile the 2016 rust source code, but it can probably do 2013, use that to compile 2014, use that to compile 2015 use that to compile 2016.<p>As long as you have a single binary from any point before the attack was introduced it shouldn&#x27;t be an issue.  The whole point is that at no point does the source code contain the trust backdoor, so you can just work forward from any binary that doesn&#x27;t have it yet.<p>if the very first version of rust binary already had it as an issue, as well as was written in rust, you could conceivably have a problem though.  then you would need an alternative compiler, however sub-optimal it might be...<p>or you could simply patch and remove the backdoor from the binary and then have it compile itself without inserting the backdoor.",
